{
  "title": "Difficulties with Leaving",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "86a2afa1915bd68d",
      "text": "If I want to fetch something, I must first go to the place there where it is available. But the fetching must begin here. And the last thing I do at the beginning here is that I, well prepared and equipped, go away from here. But why don't I do it simply by immediately turning around and disappearing wordlessly? Why do I have to stage my departure with a whole repertoire of behavioral figures?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "952e60f478eefa7f",
      "text": "Well, the fact that leaving is difficult - both for me who do it and for those I leave behind - has its reason in the ambiguity of the movement I perform there: Of what kind is the action actually, with which the fetching begins? Do I go there, to that place, where what I want to have is? Or do I go away: from this place, in which I am still now? Can I do both at the same time, do I even have to? How do those who stay behind see me when I turn my back on them in order to leave? And how can I and must I \"take into consideration\" their way of seeing me, so that my action of bringing something here for them and for us can also succeed?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "89841ca24cca39f1",
      "text": "First, I will touch on the problem of how we are able to distinguish going and going away in the first place, and briefly illustrate how helpful it is in social intercourse that this distinction is so difficult. This is followed by a brief digression on the consequences of this distinction for the forms in which we gather, assemble, and disperse. Finally and mainly, it is then to be shown that the end of the collector's presence evokes an anthropologically highly delicate situation, precarious because in it a transition takes place that endangers the existence of all involved. Between his caring attentions and his distance-creating departure, whoever leaves performs a dangerous turning away. It hurts those who stay; and it makes the one who leaves vulnerable. Ritual procedures are needed to defuse this situation and to establish a firm bond between abandonment and reliability, farewell and fidelity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fba5cfa313cb3a43",
      "text": "⇒ [[Unambiguous Action, Ambivalent Behavior]]"
    }
